&gt;  I&#39;m using JUnit 4 from Eclipse, and my test class extends DBTestCase. Using
&gt;  annotations and other JUnit 4 features, however, doesn&#39;t work from Eclipse,
&gt;  which warns that no tests can be found on the class. However, it works when
&gt;  I remove extends DBTestCase from my test class.
&gt;
&gt;  I found an example that uses a @BeforeClass annotation that manually calls
&gt;  DBUnit&#39;s methods, but I see this as a (hopefully temporary) workaround that
&gt;  you might have the right alternative to. How do I integrate DBUnit and JUnit
&gt;  4 from within Eclipse the way it was meant to be used (i.e. no workarounds)?
&gt;
&gt;  Thanks.

Hi,

I think you probably have 2 choices. Wait until DBUnit comes with
built-in support for JUnit4, similar to how JMock have provided new
functionality [1]. I don&#39;t know if that&#39;s on the DBUnit roadmap.

Secondly, use @RunWith to define the Runner that you want to use, so
that the JUnit3 runner is used.

Cheers,

James

[1] http://www.jmock.org/getting-started.html
